    "instruction": "Load metric.csv and trace.csv. Return a compact summary: (1) list unique cmdb_id values from both files; (2) for metric.csv: list unique kpi_name values, row count per kpi_name (top 20), and for each kpi_name compute global percentiles P5, P25, P50, P75, P90, P95 of the 'value' column (aggregate across all cmdb_id). Limit percentile table to one row per kpi_name. (3) for trace.csv: list unique trace_name values, row count per trace_name (top 20), and compute the same percentiles (P5..P95) for trace 'value' per trace_name. Return results as compact tables (no full time series)."
}

{
    "analysis": "The previous Executor run loaded metric.csv and trace.csv and produced global summaries: unique cmdb_id lists and global percentiles (P5, P25, P50, P75, P90, P95) for each kpi_name in metric.csv and for each trace_name in trace.csv (aggregated across cmdb_id where appropriate). These global thresholds are now available and satisfy the requirement to compute thresholds using full series before filtering to the incident window. From the summaries we can see many KPI series (CPU, Disk, Memory, network, ss_total, etc.) and several trace types (jdbc, local, csf, flyremote, etc.). Next we must identify which component-KPI series show anomalies inside the incident window (May 27, 2020 05:30–06:00 UTC+8) by comparing data points in that window against the previously computed global thresholds. We should run a bounded scan that reports per component-KPI (i.e., per cmdb_id,kpi_name for metrics and per cmdb_id,trace_name for traces) how many points in the incident window breach global P95 (high-side) or P5 (low-side), the earliest breach timestamp, and simple severity measures (e.g., max(value)/P95 for high-side breaches and P5/min(value) for low-side breaches). Limit output to top 20 candidate component-KPIs by total breach count. If no breaches are found, we will relax thresholds (e.g., P90/P10) in a follow-up step.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv and trace.csv already loaded by the kernel, do the following (return compact tables only, limit rows to top 20):\n1) For metric.csv: for each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) compute global P95 and P5 using the full available series (do NOT filter by incident window for this step). Then filter metric.csv to rows within the incident time window May 27, 2020 05:30 to 06:00 (UTC+8). For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) in that window, count high-side breaches where value >= global_P95 and low-side breaches where value <= global_P5. For each pair with at least one breach, report: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_P95, global_P5, breach_count_high, breach_count_low, total_breach_count, earliest_breach_timestamp (the earliest timestamp within window where any breach occurred), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, severity_high = max_value_in_window / global_P95 (use null if no high breach), severity_low = global_P5 / min_value_in_window (use null if no low breach). Return top 20 rows sorted by total_breach_count desc.\n2) For trace.csv: do the analogous procedure per (cmdb_id,trace_name): compute global P95 and P5 across full series; filter to the incident window; count breaches high (>=P95) and low (<=P5); for each pair with at least one breach return: cmdb_id, trace_name, global_P95, global_P5, breach_count_high, breach_count_low, total_breach_count, earliest_breach_timestamp, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, severity_high, severity_low. Return top 20 sorted by total_breach_count desc.\n3) If no rows are returned for either metrics or traces (i.e., zero breaches found), just return an explicit indicator that no P95/P5 breaches were found in the incident window so we can relax to P90/P10 in the next step.\nKeep the output compact (one row per component-KPI), and do not print full raw time series. Use kernel variables to store intermediate tables but only display the requested top-20 aggregate tables."
}

{
    "analysis": "Executor found widespread P95/P5 breaches across many DB nodes (db_001..db_005, etc.) and several docker containers (docker_001..docker_003) during the incident window. Breaches appear continuous for the entire 30-minute window (breach_count_high=30 and breach_count_low=30, earliest breach at 2020-05-27 05:30:00 CST). Several KPI thresholds are zero producing NaN severities; for non-zero thresholds severity_high/low often equals 1.0 — indicating values reached the P95/P5 exactly across the window. At this point we have global thresholds and know that many component-KPIs breached, but we have not yet grouped those breaches into consecutive faults or evaluated extremal deviation to exclude weak/significant faults. According to the diagnosis workflow, the next step is fault identification: detect consecutive anomalous sub-series (fault intervals) per (component,KPI) within the incident window, compute each fault's start time, end time, duration, extremal value and a severity score so we can later use trace analysis to localize the root cause among potentially multiple faulty components.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the cached global thresholds (global_P95 and global_P5 computed earlier) and metric.csv already loaded in the kernel, perform fault identification for metric series within the incident window May 27, 2020 05:30 to 06:00 (UTC+8):\n1) Filter metric.csv to that time window. For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) find consecutive-minute runs where value >= global_P95 (mark as 'high' breach) or value <= global_P5 (mark as 'low' breach). A consecutive run means adjacent timestamps in the window without gaps larger than one minute.\n2) For each detected run (fault) output one row with these columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, breach_type ('high' or 'low'), fault_start_timestamp, fault_end_timestamp, duration_minutes (inclusive), data_point_count, max_value_in_fault, min_value_in_fault, global_P95, global_P5, severity (for 'high' = max_value_in_fault / global_P95, for 'low' = global_P5 / min_value_in_fault; if divider is zero set severity to null), and a simple significance flag 'significant' = True if severity >= 1.5 (i.e., > 50% beyond threshold) else False.\n3) Return the top 20 faults sorted by data_point_count desc then severity desc. Keep the output compact (one row per fault). If no faults are found, return an explicit indicator 'no faults found in metric window'."
}

